Poodle Thrusters:<br>
The Poodle thruster concept is derived from radioisotope thermoelectric generator (RTG) technology. Basically, the thermoelectric converters from the RTG are removed, and energy from the RTG nuclear fuel capsules is used to heat a propellant &quot;working fluid,&quot; such as hydrogen, water, helium, etc., to temperatures of 1500 to 2000°C and then expand the hot gas through a nozzle. Thus, the Poodle thruster is a small nuclear thermal rocket operating at a power level of about 5 kW with a specific impulse (with hydrogen) of 700 to 800 lbf-s/lbm and a thrust around 1.3 to 1.5 N (~0.3 lbf). The thruster would be about 33 cm long by 10 cm in diameter, and weigh about 13.6 kg. Mission applications for the Poodle thruster are similar to those for Arcjets &lt;../Electric/03.html&gt;, which have a similar overall performance, such as 30-day LEO-to-GEO transfers, attitude control, and planetary missions. The thruster was designed to use hydrogen gas boil-off from a liquid hydrogen tank so as to simplify cryogenic liquid hydrogen storage thermal control requirements. <br>
<br>
Unlike a conventional RTG, which uses a nuclear fuel such as plutonium (Pu) with a long half-life (for long-duration missions requiring a nearly steady electric power output), the Poodle thruster uses polonium (Po210) with a short half-life (138 days) to improve power density and simplify safe-orbit decay lifetime (10 years) requirements. However, like a conventional RTG (and unlike a traditional NERVA-type nuclear thermal rocket &lt;02.html&gt;), the Poodle thruster is always &quot;on&quot; in the sense that the nuclear fuel is continuously producing energy. Thus, a provision must be made for cooling the thruster when not in use.&quot;<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE IMAGE START--><img src="http://image1ex.villagephotos.com/1872341.jpg"/><!--EZCODE IMAGE END--><!--EZCODE IMAGE START--><img src="http://image1ex.villagephotos.com/1872376.jpg"/><!--EZCODE IMAGE END--><br>
<br>
Fission Fragment Propulsion:<br>
Fission-fragment propulsion involves permitting the energetic fragments produced in the nuclear fission process to directly escape from the reactor; thus, the fission fragments, moving with a velocity of several percent of the speed of light, are the propellant working fluid. Because these fragments are heavily ionized, they can be directed by magnetic fields to produce thrust for propulsion. Specific impulse in excess of 1 million lbf-s/lbm is possible. <br>
To permit the fragments to escape from the nuclear fuel and reactor, a low density (but critical) reactor must be constructed. The images below depict designs developed by the Idaho National Engineering Laboratory (INEL) and the Lawrence Livermore National Laboratory (LLNL), thin graphite fibers with nuclear fuel cladded on the surface are used. These fibers are then arranged radially on large revolving wheels which rotate the fibers through a reactor. As the fibers rotate through the reactor, they fission. Since the fibers are very thin, they permit the fragments to escape. The fibers then rotate out of the reactor where they can radiate their waste heat to space, and charged fissioned-fragment nuclei accelerate out of the of the reactor in a direction designated by carefully constructed magnetic fields.<br>
